    newsArticle1Title: "Corona Emergency Aid Recovery",
    newsArticle1Date: "September 12, 2025",
    newsArticle1Category: "Tax Law",
    newsArticle1Subtitle: "Recovery of Corona Emergency Aid: Current Developments",
    newsArticle1Intro: "Many Hessian entrepreneurs have recently received mail from the Kassel government presidency. Five years after the Corona pandemic, the state is demanding a so-called \"feedback\" on the Corona emergency aid that was paid out at the time. In the worst case, there is a threat of recovery of the emergency aid.",
    newsArticle1Section1Title: "Why refunds now?",
    newsArticle1Section1Text1: "The Corona emergency aid from spring 2020 was intended to protect companies from economic hardship without bureaucracy. The promise was quick help without lengthy examination procedures. However, the approvals were subject to reservation: those who could not later prove a real liquidity shortage should repay the Corona aid.",
    newsArticle1Section1Text2: "The Kassel government presidency has set up a digital feedback portal for this purpose. Entrepreneurs must provide their income, expenses and own funds for the months March to May 2020 there.",
    newsArticle1Section2Title: "Current case law: Recovery not always lawful",
    newsArticle1Section2Intro: "Since 2021, the recoveries have been keeping the administrative courts busy nationwide. The judgments are inconsistent - and this opens up opportunities for those affected:",
    newsArticle1Section2Item1: "OVG NRW, decision of 17.03.2023: Recoveries only permissible if there was actually no liquidity shortage",
    newsArticle1Section2Item2: "VG Düsseldorf, judgment of 16.08.2022: For the assessment of legality, the funding practice of the state during the application process was decisive",
    newsArticle1Section2Item3: "VG Karlsruhe, judgment of 11.10.2024: Decisions cannot be revoked on the grounds that the funds were not used to overcome a liquidity shortage",
    newsArticle1Section3Title: "Legal attack points against recoveries",
    newsArticle1Section3Intro: "Affected entrepreneurs have various approaches:",
    newsArticle1Section3Item1: "Limitation: Recoveries may already be time-barred (§ 195 BGB)",
    newsArticle1Section3Item2: "Forfeiture: Five years of inactivity can establish trust protection",
    newsArticle1Section3Item3: "Unclear conditions: Contradictory formulations from 2020 speak for the entrepreneur",
    newsArticle1Section3Item4: "Formal errors: Blanket or poorly justified decisions are attackable",
    newsArticle1Section3Item5: "Proportionality: Authorities must check whether recoveries threaten existence",
    newsArticle1Section4Title: "What entrepreneurs should do now",
