    newsArticle5Title: "Non-Profit Status: Four-Sphere Model",
    newsArticle5Date: "December 24, 2025",
    newsArticle5Category: "Non-Profit Status",
    newsArticle5Subtitle: "Four-Sphere Model and Timely Use of Funds",
    newsArticle5Text1: "Non-profit corporations are divided tax-wise into ideal area, asset management, purpose business and commercial business. This system decides on corporate tax/business tax liability and is also decisive for VAT classification.",
    newsArticle5Text2: "A central point is the timely use of funds for statutory purposes – it is a focus of examination and a prerequisite for status. Associations benefit if they consistently assign activities, keep records and document fund usage reports cleanly.",
    newsArticle5Section1Title: "Purpose Business and Reduced VAT Rate (§ 12 Para. 2 No. 8a VAT Act)",
    newsArticle5Section1Text1: "Services in the purpose business can be subject to the reduced VAT rate if they directly serve to realize the non-profit purposes. The distinction from the commercial business, which is regularly subject to the standard rate, is critical.",
    newsArticle5Section1Text2: "The examination is case-by-case and depends heavily on competitive situation, service content and charter reference. For associations, this means: charter, service description and actual implementation must match. Unclear assignments can lead to tax back-claims.",
    newsArticle5CTATitle: "Questions about non-profit status? We are happy to advise you.",
    newsArticle5CTAButton: "Contact us",
    
    newsArticle6Title: "VAT Updates 2025",
    newsArticle6Date: "December 17, 2025",
    newsArticle6Category: "VAT",
    newsArticle6Subtitle: "Educational Services (§ 4 No. 21 VAT Act)",
    newsArticle6Text1: "The tax exemption for educational services is strongly procedure-dependent: often a certificate from the responsible state authority is required that confirms proper preparation for profession/examination. This decision acts in practice like a basic decision and binds the tax administration, making the procedure step central.",
    newsArticle6Text2: "Educational providers should set up service offerings, contracts, curriculum and certificate management tax-consistently. This significantly reduces risks from misqualification and incorrect invoicing.",
    newsArticle6Section1Title: "E-Charging: VAT Classification as Electricity Supply",
    newsArticle6Section1Text1: "Charging of electric vehicles is regularly treated as a unified supply of electricity. Ancillary services such as app use, activation, support or reservation usually share the fate of the main service. For operators, this creates clarity in service description and invoicing, but reduces design freedom in \"splitting\".",
    newsArticle6Section1Text2: "Clean contract and billing models are decisive, especially in roaming or platform constellations.",
    newsArticle6Section2Title: "Incorrect Tax Statement (§ 14c VAT Act) and ECJ Limits",
    newsArticle6Section2Text1: "If an entrepreneur states VAT too high (e.g., 19% instead of 7%), a tax liability under § 14c can generally arise to avoid input tax risks for the recipient. An important limitation concerns invoices to end consumers: there, the § 14c tax liability can fall under ECJ line because no input tax deduction threatens. In the B2B area, the risk usually remains.",
    newsArticle6Section3Title: "Small Business Regulation and Abuse through Splitting",
    newsArticle6Section3Text1: "The small business regulation is increasingly critically examined when revenues are \"artificially\" distributed among several persons to stay below thresholds. In abusive cases, a consolidation can occur, causing the status to be lost retroactively. This leads to massive risks: back-taxation, invoice corrections and possibly interest consequences.",
    newsArticle6Section3Text2: "Those who use small structures should be able to prove substance, actual service provision and separate entrepreneur status cleanly.",
    newsArticle6CTATitle: "VAT questions? We help with correct classification.",
