    newsArticle7Title: "Payroll Tax: Company Cars and Payroll",
    newsArticle7Date: "December 10, 2025",
    newsArticle7Category: "Payroll Tax",
    newsArticle7Subtitle: "Company Cars: Prima Facie Evidence and Logbook Requirements",
    newsArticle7Text1: "For company cars made available, the tax administration often assumes private use (prima facie evidence). A private use ban only helps if it is clearly agreed, actually enforced and controlled. A logbook can precisely prove the private portion, but must be formally correct – especially with digital solutions (timely, gap-free, changes traceable).",
    newsArticle7Text2: "For companies, the topic is a classic because small formal errors quickly lead to high back-taxations.",
    newsArticle7Section1Title: "Cash Wage vs. Benefit in Kind, bKV and Thresholds",
    newsArticle7Section1Text1: "The distinction between cash wage and benefit in kind often decides on tax exemption or lump-sum options. With employer-financed insurance (e.g., company health insurance), benefit in kind may be present, while subsidies are rather cash wage – this significantly changes the application of thresholds.",
    newsArticle7Section1Text2: "The claim structure is important: if there is a payout claim, the benefit often fails. Payroll processes should therefore evaluate advantages standardized and document cleanly.",
    newsArticle7Section2Title: "§ 37b Income Tax Act: Lump-Sum Taxation of Benefits and Timing",
    newsArticle7Section2Text1: "§ 37b Income Tax Act enables lump-sum taxation of certain benefits to business friends or employees. In practice, distinctions and allocations are decisive (e.g., at mixed events, boxes/business seats, entertainment portions). Moreover, timing is critical: the lump-sum must be correctly integrated into the payroll process and is not arbitrarily \"catchable\".",
    newsArticle7Section3Title: "DTA Allocation for Foreign Activities",
    newsArticle7Section3Text1: "For cross-border activities, wages often must be allocated to domestic and foreign according to actual working days. This requires reliable documentation of travel days, activity locations and contract bases. Errors not only affect payroll tax but can also trigger social insurance follow-up questions.",
    newsArticle7Section3Text2: "Companies should therefore establish standardized travel and payroll reporting.",
    newsArticle7CTATitle: "Payroll tax questions? We support you with correct payroll.",
