    newsArticle8Title: "Income Tax: Severance Payments and Home Office",
    newsArticle8Date: "December 3, 2025",
    newsArticle8Category: "Income Tax",
    newsArticle8Subtitle: "Severance Payments and Fifth Rule (§ 34 Income Tax Act)",
    newsArticle8Text1: "Severance payments can be taxed at a reduced rate if the requirements of the fifth rule are met – the core is the accumulation of income. The benefit often fails if severance payments flow in spread over several years or the income effect in the payout year is not clearly increased. Therefore, the design of the inflow timing (lump sum vs. installments) is often decisive.",
    newsArticle8Text2: "For employees, early tax scenario calculation is recommended before termination agreements are finally concluded.",
    newsArticle8Section1Title: "Home Office and Home Office Lump Sum",
    newsArticle8Section1Text1: "The home office is only fully deductible tax-wise under strict conditions, especially if it forms the center of professional activity. In addition, the home office lump sum exists as a pragmatic solution for days when work was done exclusively at home.",
    newsArticle8Section1Text2: "In practice, the distinction is important because proof and legal consequences are different. Structured documentation of work days and activity profiles helps avoid discussions in assessment.",
    newsArticle8Section2Title: "Double Household and Second Home Tax",
    newsArticle8Section2Text1: "Double household requires an own household at the life center and a professionally caused second home at the activity location. Accommodation costs are basically limited to 1,000 € per month domestically, whereby individual cost types are to be assessed separately. Particularly relevant: The second home tax can be additionally deductible and does not necessarily fall under the 1,000 € cap.",
    newsArticle8Section2Text2: "For recognition and optimal assertion, clean proof (rental contracts, home trips, life center) is decisive.",
    newsArticle8Section3Title: "Real Estate Rental: Declining Depreciation and Acquisition-Related Production Costs",
    newsArticle8Section3Text1: "For new residential buildings, declining depreciation is a significant tax lever because it can enable higher depreciation in the initial years. At the same time, caution is advised with renovations after acquisition: if maintenance/modernization costs exceed the 15% threshold within three years (relative to building costs net), they become acquisition-related production costs and are only deductible via depreciation.",
    newsArticle8Section3Text2: "This massively affects liquidity and renovation planning. Those who acquire real estate should plan measures temporally and in content so that tax effects do not unintentionally flip.",
    newsArticle8Section4Title: "Cryptocurrencies in Private Assets (§ 23 Income Tax Act)",
    newsArticle8Section4Text1: "Crypto gains in private assets can be taxable if less than a year lies between acquisition and sale/exchange. Tax-relevant is not only the sale in euros, but often also the exchange from coin to coin. This makes a complete transaction history (incl. acquisition dates, fees, wallet/exchange data) practically indispensable.",
    newsArticle8Section5Title: "Loss Offset for Capital Investments and Futures",
    newsArticle8Section5Text1: "For capital investments, loss offset is a recurring design and dispute field because different rules apply depending on product type. A significant change is the lifting of certain strict offset restrictions for futures, enabling losses to be offset again more broadly with capital gains. At the same time, other limitations remain relevant.",
    newsArticle8Section5Text2: "Investors benefit from clean categorization of losses and tax annual planning instead of \"pure portfolio consideration\".",
    newsArticle8CTATitle: "Questions about income tax? We are happy to advise you.",
