    newsArticle9Title: "Photovoltaics: Tax Design",
    newsArticle9Date: "November 26, 2025",
    newsArticle9Category: "Photovoltaics",
    newsArticle9Subtitle: "Income Tax Exemption for Small Systems (§ 3 No. 72 Income Tax Act)",
    newsArticle9Text1: "For many smaller PV systems, a far-reaching income tax exemption applies, typically depending on performance limits and object reference (e.g., single-family/two-family house). The exemption reduces declaration obligations and defuses the question of profit-making intent in many standard cases.",
    newsArticle9Text2: "However, the distinction remains important whether the system is operated privately or assigned to an existing business – for example with relevant self-consumption in the business. If limits are exceeded, classic examinations (profit-making intent, business income/expenses) return.",
    newsArticle9Section1Title: "VAT Zero Rate (0%) and Consequences for Input Tax",
    newsArticle9Section1Text1: "For delivery and installation of certain PV systems, a 0% VAT rate applies, which significantly simplifies practice. At the same time, this often leads to no input tax deduction from the acquisition because no VAT arises.",
    newsArticle9Section1Text2: "The clean classification of the operator and documentation of requirements is important, as the performing entrepreneur needs proof. Operators and installers benefit if offer, invoice, operator declaration and documentation are consistently designed.",
    newsArticle9Section2Title: "Investment Deduction (IAB) and Interactions",
    newsArticle9Section2Text1: "The interaction between IAB and PV tax exemption is a frequent pitfall: an IAB formed in earlier years cannot be arbitrarily transferred to investments if the later system is treated tax-free. This can cause investment decisions (timing, system size, assignment) to have unexpected tax effects.",
